      <unit unitid="SubSec_ScalarMultiplicationVector">
         <titles>
            <title>Multiplication of a Vector by a Scalar</title>
            <plain.title>Scalar Multiplication</plain.title>
         </titles>
         <body>
            <block>
               <block.body>
                  <def type="Definition" id="Def_ScalarMultiplicationVector">
                     <caption>Multiplication of a Vector by a Scalar</caption>
                     <associate type="Example">
                        <showme.pack.ref showmePackID="Exa_MultiplyVectorByScalar"/>
                        <info>
                           <info.caption>Examples of multiplying a vector by a scalar</info.caption>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Thus, when multiplying a vector by a number <math>
                                    <latex>t</latex>
                                 </math>, we just multiply each coordinate by <math>
                                    <latex>t</latex>
                                 </math>. – View some examples of this.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </associate>
                     <def.body>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>The scalar product of a vector <math>
                                 <latex>\Vect{x}=(x_1,\dots ,x_n)</latex>
                              </math> in <math>
                                 <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                              </math> by a number <math>
                                 <latex>t</latex>
                              </math> in <math>
                                 <latex>\RNr</latex>
                              </math> is
					</para.body>
                           <index.glossary>
                              <term>multiplication</term>
                              <term>of a vector by a number</term>
                              <info>
                                 <math.display>
                                    <latex>t\cdot \Vect{x}\ =\ t\cdot (x_1,\dots ,x_n)\ :=\ (tx_1,\dots ,tx_n)</latex>
                                 </math.display>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Click to jump to the definition</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </index.glossary>
                        </para>
                        <math.display>
                           <latex>t\cdot \Vect{x}\ =\ t\cdot (x_1,\dots ,x_n)\ :=\ (tx_1,\dots ,tx_n).</latex>
                        </math.display>
                     </def.body>
                  </def>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>The multiplication of a vector <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math> by a scalar <math>
                           <latex>t</latex>
                        </math> has a useful geometric interpretation: it corresponds to <subordinate>
                           <hot>multiplying the length</hot>
                           <info>
                              <info.caption>Geometric Interpretation of Scalar Multiplication</info.caption>
                              <para>
                                 <para.body>When we multiply a vector <math>
                                       <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                                    </math> by a number (a scalar) <math>
                                       <latex>t</latex>
                                    </math>, we keep the direction of <math>
                                       <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                                    </math> and multiply its length by <math>
                                       <latex>t</latex>
                                    </math>. The reason for this is the law of similar triangles:</para.body>
                              </para>
                              <para align="center">
                                 <para.body/>
                              </para>
                           </info>
                        </subordinate> of <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math> by <math>
                           <latex>t</latex>
                        </math>, while keeping the direction of <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math> unchanged. Om other words, the vectors <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>t\Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math> are parallel.</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <def type="Definition" id="Def_ParallelVectors">
                     <caption>Parallel Vectors</caption>
                     <associate type="Illustration">
                        <unit.ref unitId="Illust_ScalarMultiplicationOfVectors"/>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Click for an illustration of parallel vectors.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </associate>
                     <def.body>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>A vector <math>
                                 <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                              </math> is parallel to a nonzero vector <math>
                                 <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                              </math> if
					</para.body>
                           <index.glossary>
                              <term>parallel</term>
                              <term>vectors</term>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Definition of the concept</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </index.glossary>
                           <index.glossary>
                              <term>vectors</term>
                              <term>parallel</term>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Definition of the concept</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </index.glossary>
                        </para>
                        <para align="center">
                           <para.body>there exists a number <math>
                                 <latex>t</latex>
                              </math> with <math>
                                 <latex>\Vect{y} = t\cdot \Vect{x}</latex>
                              </math>.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </def.body>
                  </def>
               </block.body>
